<subSubSection pageId="68" pageNumber="69" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="68.[151,1437,1672,2023]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1672,1698]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schrottky" baseAuthorityYear="1909" box="[280,549,1672,1698]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Augochlora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="68" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phoemonoe">
<emphasis box="[280,549,1672,1698]" italics="true" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">Augochlora phoemonoe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the T1 apex inflexed (
<figureCitation box="[846,932,1672,1699]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="10.[151,250,760,784]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,737]" captionTargetId="figure-19@10.[151,1435,181,737]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 2. Male T1. A) Augochlora braziliensis Vachal; B) Augochlora thusnelda (Schrottky). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4392353" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4392353/files/figure.png" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
) and a spiniform projection with rounded tip on S1 (as in 
<figureCitation box="[291,373,1708,1735]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1783,1807]" captionTargetBox="[172,1421,326,1746]" captionTargetId="figure-189@9.[155,1432,315,1759]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 1. A–C) Female mandible, anterior view. A) Augochlora aurinasis (Vachal); B) Augochlora daphnis Smith; C) Augochlora genalis sp. nov. Scale bar: 0.2 mm. D–G) Female mid trochanter, anterior view. D) Augochlora nausicaa (Schrottky); E) Augochlora francisca (Schrottky); F) Augochlora phoemonoe (Schrottky); G) Augochlora mulleri Cockerell. H–L) Female metasoma, anterior portion (T1 and S1), lateral view. H) Augochlora thusnelda (Schrottky); I) Augochlora nausicaa (Schrottky); J) Augochlora braziliensis (Vachal); K) Augochlora francisca Schrottky; L) Augochlora phoemonoe (Schrottky). D–L not in scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4392349" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4392349/files/figure.png" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">Fig. 1L</figureCitation>
) of females. These are diagnosed by the mid trochanter ventral margin widely rounded and the pronotum dorsolateral angles not projected. The latter character differs both males and females from 
<taxonomicName authority="(Moure, 1943)" baseAuthorityName="Moure" baseAuthorityYear="1943" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Augochlora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="68" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="micans">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">Augochlora micans</emphasis>
(Moure, 1943)
</taxonomicName>
, a similar species found in S„o Paulo and northwards. Males are also characterized by the yellowish F1, T3 weakly punctate near base and strongly imbricate on disc, and T2 loosely imbricate near marginal area.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="68" pageNumber="69" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="68.[151,1437,1672,2023]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1888,1914]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">Comments.</emphasis>
We examined the 
<typeStatus box="[545,643,1888,1914]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moure" authorityYear="1940" box="[681,784,1889,1915]" class="Insecta" family="Hymenoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Odontochlora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="68" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="neivai">
<emphasis box="[681,784,1889,1915]" italics="true" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">O. neivai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and it corresponds to a typical 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schrottky" baseAuthorityYear="1909" box="[1138,1299,1888,1915]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Augochlora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="68" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phoemonoe">
<emphasis box="[1138,1299,1888,1915]" italics="true" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">A. phoemonoe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
female. Social behavior was studied by 
<bibRefCitation author="Dalmazzo, M. &amp; Roig-Alsina, A." box="[483,849,1924,1951]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69" pagination="315 - 323" refId="ref73795" refString="Dalmazzo, M. &amp; Roig-Alsina, A. (2015) Social biology of Augochlora (Augochlora) phoemonoe (Hymenoptera, Halictidae) reared in laboratory nests. Insectes sociaux, 62 (3), 315 - 323. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 00040 - 015 - 0412 - 8" type="journal article" year="2015">Dalmazzo &amp; Roig-Alsina (2015</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Dalmazzo, M. &amp; Roig-Alsina, A." box="[862,933,1924,1951]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69" pagination="852 - 861" refId="ref73911" refString="Dalmazzo, M. &amp; Roig-Alsina, A. (2018 b) Dominant-subordinate social interactions and subordinate behavioral responses in the primitively eusocial sweat bee Augochlora phoemonoe (Hymenoptera: Halictidae). Apidologie, 49 (6), 852 - 861. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 13592 - 018 - 0609 - 8" type="journal article" year="2018">2018b</bibRefCitation>
) over nests reared in laboratory. For species description and additional comments see 
<bibRefCitation author="Dalmazzo, M. &amp; Roig-Alsina, A." box="[614,984,1960,1987]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69" pagination="15 - 32" refId="ref73683" refString="Dalmazzo, M. &amp; Roig-Alsina, A. (2011) Revision of the species of the New World genus Augochlora (Hymenoptera, Halictidae) occurring in the southern temperate areas of its range. Zootaxa, 2750, 15 - 32. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2750.1.2" type="journal article" year="2011">Dalmazzo &amp; Roig-Alsina (2011)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="69" lastPageNumber="70" pageId="68" pageNumber="69" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="68.[151,1437,1672,2023]" lastBlockId="69.[151,1436,151,213]" lastPageId="69" lastPageNumber="70" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1996,2022]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species is found in the Brazilian states of Paraná, Rio Grande do Sul, Santa Catarina, and S„o Paulo. In 
<collectingCountry box="[310,424,151,177]" name="Argentina" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, the species is recorded in the provinces of 
<collectingRegion box="[919,1073,151,177]" country="Argentina" name="Ciudad Autonoma de Buenos Aires" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Buenos Aires</collectingRegion>
, Cordoba, 
<collectingRegion box="[1196,1319,151,177]" country="Argentina" name="Entre Rios" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Entre Rios</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[1331,1432,151,177]" country="Argentina" name="Formosa" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Formosa</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[151,267,187,213]" country="Argentina" name="La Pampa" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">La Pampa</collectingRegion>
, Misiones, 
<collectingRegion box="[395,454,187,213]" country="Argentina" name="Salta" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Salta</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[465,565,187,213]" country="Argentina" name="Santa Fe" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Santa Fé</collectingRegion>
, and 
<collectingRegion box="[623,732,187,213]" country="Argentina" name="Tucuman" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Tucumán</collectingRegion>
. The species is also found in 
<collectingCountry box="[1058,1162,187,213]" name="Paraguay" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1217,1317,187,213]" name="Uruguay" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Uruguay</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
